David Plass wrote:

&gt; When writing test cases my fingers automatically type:
&gt; 
&gt;     public void testTheMethodBeingTested() throws Exception {
           fail(&quot;Not yet implemented&quot;);
&gt;     }

I just added a line of code you might like in all your tests. Don&#39;t 
remove the fail() statement until you&#39;re certain you&#39;ve written the test 
correctly. It avoids false positives.

Better yet, import this code template into Eclipse:

&lt;?xml version=&quot;1.0&quot; encoding=&quot;UTF-8&quot;?&gt;
&lt;templates&gt;
     &lt;template id=&quot;org.eclipse.jdt.ui.templates.test&quot; name=&quot;test&quot; 
description=&quot;test method&quot; context=&quot;java&quot; enabled=&quot;true&quot; 
deleted=&quot;false&quot;&gt;public void test${name}() throws Exception {
	${cursor}
	fail(&quot;Not yet implemented&quot;);
}&lt;/template&gt;
&lt;/templates&gt;

